# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: barbulanympha
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The **acorn** is the nut of the oaks and their close relatives (genera *Quercus*, *Notholithocarpus* and *Lithocarpus*, in the family Fagaceae); alternatively known as **glans**.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] It usually contains a seedling surrounded by two cotyledons (seedling leaves), enclosed in a tough shell known as the pericarp, and borne in a cup-shaped cupule.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns take between 5 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see the list of *Quercus* species for details of oak classification, in which acorn morphology and phenology are important factors.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The word *acorn* (earlier *akerne*, and *acharn*) is related to the Gothic name *akran*, which had the sense of "fruit of the unenclosed land".
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Chaucer spoke of "achornes of okes" in the 14th century.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] By degrees, popular etymology connected the word both with "corn" and "oak-horn", and the spelling changed accordingly.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] 15th–16th century) derives from association with *ac* (Old English: "oak") + *corn*.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The Latin *glans* as found in many literature regarding it originally applies to any nut is the root of several Romance words for the acorn (the French *gland*, Catalan *gla*, Italian *ghianda*) cognate to Greek βάλανος, which also extends to the vascular penile tip from similarity in shape.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns play an important role in forest ecology when oaks are plentiful or dominant in the landscape.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed mast.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Wildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as jays, pigeons, some ducks, and several species of woodpeckers.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Small mammals that feed on acorns include mice, squirrels and several other rodents.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] One beetle species, *Thorectes lusitanicus*, also feeds on acorns.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns have a large influence on small rodents in their habitats, as large acorn yields help rodent populations to grow.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Large mammals such as pigs, bears, and deer also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] In Spain, Portugal and the New Forest region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in *dehesas* (large oak groves) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their tannins, such as horses and cattle, especially if eaten in excess.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The larvae of some moths and weevils also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of protein, carbohydrates and fats, as well as the minerals calcium, phosphorus and potassium, and the vitamin niacin.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Total food energy in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns also contain bitter tannins, the amount varying with the species.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Since tannins, which are plant polyphenols, interfere with an animal's ability to metabolize protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause ulceration and kidney failure.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Animals that cache acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has percolated through them to leach out the tannins.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Species of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, astringent, and potentially irritating if eaten raw.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] This is particularly true of the acorns of American red oaks and English oaks.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The acorns of white oaks, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Tannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Being rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or molder easily and must be carefully stored.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns of the white oak group, *Leucobalanus*, typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns are too heavy for wind dispersal, so they require other ways to spread.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Oaks therefore depend on biological seed dispersal agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of 20–30 m (70–100 ft) from the parent tree.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Many animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as squirrels and jays serve as seed dispersal agents.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Even though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to eat them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Scatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible lignins that form the root.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] In some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary staple, though they have largely been replaced by grains and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Several cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Raw acorns are 28% water, 41% carbohydrates, 24% fat, and 6% protein (table).
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw acorns supply 387 calories and are a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of vitamin B6, folate, copper, and manganese (table).
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Dental microwear suggests that Neanderthals in Belgium consumed acorns among other hard foods.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Many modern human cultures relied on acorns, such as the Ancient Greek lower classes and the Japanese (during the Jōmon period), for instance.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] In antiquity, Pliny the Elder noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter tannins in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Varieties preferred by Native Americans, such as *Quercus kelloggii* (California black oak), may be easier to prepare or more palatable.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Roasted acorn flour is a main ingredient in sweet cakes special to Kurdish areas of Iran and Iraq.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns are a traditional food of many indigenous peoples of North America, and long served an especially important role for Californian Native Americans, where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] In the San Francisco Bay Area acorns found were often associated with grinding tools.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Stone tools like hammerstone and anvil, millingstones, and mortar and pestle help crack open the acorn and grind the acorn into dust.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns and balanophagy (acorn-eating [fr]) were associated with ideas of primitive life and Arcadia in classical literature and beyond.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] A motif in Roman architecture, also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an ornament on cutlery, furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on finials at Westminster Abbey.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The acorn was used frequently by both Union and Confederate forces during the American Civil War.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Modern US Army Cavalry Scout campaign hats still retain traces of the acorn today.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The acorn is the symbol for the National Trails of England and Wales, and is used for the waymarks on these paths.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the University of Connecticut.
[src:barbulanympha/acorn] Acorns are also used as charges in heraldry.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] The International Society of Protistologists, the recognised body for taxonomy of protozoa, recommended in 2012 that the term Unikont be changed to Amorphea because the name "Unikont" is based on a hypothesized synapomorphy that the ISOP authors and other scientists later rejected.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] It includes amoebozoa, opisthokonts, and apusomonads.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Thomas Cavalier-Smith proposed a new phylum: Sulcozoa, which consists of the subphyla Apusozoa (Apusomonadida and Breviatea), and Varisulca, which includes the taxa Diphyllatea, Discocelida, Mantamonadida, Planomonadida and Rigifilida.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Further work by Cavalier-Smith showed that Sulcozoa is paraphyletic.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Apusozoa also appears to be paraphyletic.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Varisulca has been redefined to include planomonads, *Mantamonas* and *Collodictyon*.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] A new taxon has been created - Glissodiscea - for the planomonads and *Mantamonas*.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Again, the validity of this revised taxonomy awaits confirmation.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Amoebozoa seems to be monophyletic with two major branches: Conosa and Lobosa.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Conosa is divided into the aerobic infraphylum Semiconosia (Mycetozoa and Variosea) and secondarily anaerobic Archamoebae.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Lobosa consists entirely of non-flagellated lobose amoebae and has been divided into two classes: Discosea, which have flattened cells, and Tubulinea, which has predominantly tube-shaped pseudopodia.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] The group includes eukaryotic cells that, for the most part, have a single emergent flagellum, or are amoebae with no flagella.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] The unikonts include opisthokonts (animals, fungi, and related forms) and Amoebozoa.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] By contrast, other well-known eukaryotic groups, which more often have two emergent flagella (although there are many exceptions), are often referred to as bikonts.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Bikonts include Archaeplastida (plants and relatives) and SAR supergroup, the Cryptista, Haptista, Telonemia and Picozoa.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] One view of the great kingdoms and their stem groups.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] The Metamonada are hard to place, being sister possibly to Discoba or to Malawimonadida or being a paraphyletic group external to all other eukaryotes.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Eukaryotes are thought to have emerged within the archaeal phylum Promethearchaeota.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] The unikonts have a triple-gene fusion that is lacking in the bikonts.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] The three genes that are fused together in the unikonts, but not bacteria or bikonts, encode enzymes for synthesis of the pyrimidine nucleotides: carbamoyl phosphate synthase, dihydroorotase and aspartate carbamoyltransferase.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] This must have involved a double fusion, a rare pair of events, supporting the shared ancestry of Opisthokonta and Amoebozoa.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] Cavalier-Smith originally proposed that unikonts ancestrally had a single flagellum and single basal body.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] This is unlikely, however, as flagellated opisthokonts, as well as some flagellated Amoebozoa, including *Breviata*, actually have two basal bodies, as in typical 'bikonts' (even though only one is flagellated in most unikonts).
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] This paired arrangement can also be seen in the organization of centrioles in typical animal cells.
[src:barbulanympha/amorphea] In spite of the name of the group, the common ancestor of all 'unikonts' was probably a cell with two basal bodies.
[src:barbulanympha/anaeramoeba] As the name implies, *Anaeramoeba* are anaerobic amoeboid organisms which form a fan-like shape similar to that of *Flamella*.
[src:barbulanympha/anaeramoeba] At least two species can also sometimes assume flagellate forms; with either two or four flagella.
[src:barbulanympha/anaeramoeba] They contain double-membrane bound organelles called hydrogenosomes, which is a type of mitochondria-related organelles (MROs) and assumed to be derived from mitochondria, to perform metabolism in anaerobic environments.
[src:barbulanympha/anaeramoeba] The hydrogenosomes in *Anaeramoeba* are closely associated with H2-consuming bacterial symbionts, which are enveloped by *Anaeramoeba* host's membrane called symbiosome.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] Anaphase starts when the anaphase promoting complex marks an inhibitory chaperone called securin for destruction by ubiquitylating it.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] Securin is a protein which inhibits a protease known as separase.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] The destruction of securin unleashes separase which then breaks down cohesin, a protein responsible for holding sister chromatids together.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] At this point, three subclasses of microtubule unique to mitosis are involved in creating the forces necessary to separate the chromatids: kinetochore microtubules, interpolar microtubules, and astral microtubules.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] The centromeres are split, and the sister chromatids are pulled toward the poles by kinetochore microtubules.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] They take on a V-shape or Y-shape as they are pulled to either pole.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] While the chromosomes are drawn to each side of the cell, interpolar microtubules and astral microtubules generate forces that stretch the cell into an oval.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] Once anaphase is complete, the cell moves into telophase.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] Anaphase is characterized by two distinct motions.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] The first of these, anaphase A, moves chromosomes to either pole of a dividing cell (marked by centrosomes, from which mitotic microtubules are generated and organised).
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] The movement for this is primarily generated by the action of kinetochores, and a subclass of microtubule called kinetochore microtubules.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] The second motion, anaphase B, involves the separation of these poles from each other.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] The movement for this is primarily generated by the action of interpolar microtubules and astral microtubules.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] A combination of different forces have been observed acting on chromatids in anaphase A, but the primary force is exerted centrally.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] Microtubules attach to the midpoint of chromosomes (the centromere) via protein complexes (kinetochores).
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] The attached microtubules depolymerise and shorten, which together with motor proteins creates movement that pulls chromosomes towards centrosomes located at each pole of the cell.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] The second part of anaphase is driven by its own distinct mechanisms.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] Interpolar microtubules begin at each centrosome and join at the equator of the dividing cell.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] They push against one another, causing each centrosome to move further apart.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] Meanwhile, astral microtubules begin at each centrosome and join with the cell membrane.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] This allows them to pull each centrosome closer to the cell membrane.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] Movement created by these microtubules is generated by a combination of microtubule growth or shrinking, and by motor proteins such as dyneins or kinesins.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] Anaphase accounts for approximately 1% of the cell cycle's duration.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] It begins with the regulated triggering of the metaphase-to-anaphase transition.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] Metaphase ends with the destruction of B cyclin.
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] B cyclin is marked with ubiquitin which flags it for destruction by proteasomes, which is required for the function of metaphase cyclin-dependent kinases (M-Cdks).
[src:barbulanympha/anaphase] In essence, Activation of the Anaphase-promoting complex (APC) causes the APC to cleave the M-phase cyclin and the inhibitory protein securin which activates the separase protease to cleave the cohesin subunits holding the chromatids together.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The **Appalachian Mountains**, often called the **Appalachians**, are a mountain range in eastern to northeastern North America.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The term "Appalachian" refers to several different regions and mountain systems associated with the mountain range, and its surrounding terrain.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The general definition used is one followed by the United States Geological Survey and the Geological Survey of Canada to describe the respective countries' physiographic regions.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The U.S. uses the term Appalachian Highlands and Canada uses the term Appalachian Uplands; the Appalachian Mountains are not synonymous with the Appalachian Plateau, which is one of the seven provinces of the Appalachian Highlands.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The highest peak of the mountain range is Mount Mitchell in North Carolina at 6,684 feet (2,037 m), which is also the highest point in the United States east of the Mississippi River.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The range is older than the other major mountain range in North America, the Rocky Mountains of the west.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Some of the outcrops in the Appalachians contain rocks formed during the Precambrian.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The geologic processes that led to the formation of the Appalachian Mountains started 1.1 billion years ago.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The first mountain range in the region was created when the continents of Laurentia and Amazonia collided, creating a supercontinent called Rodinia.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The collision of these continents caused the rocks to be folded and faulted, creating the first mountains in the region.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Many of the rocks and minerals that were formed during that event can currently be seen at the surface of the present Appalachian range.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Around 480 million years ago, geologic processes began that led to three distinct orogenic eras that created much of the surface structure seen in today's Appalachians.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] During this period, mountains once reached elevations similar to those of the Alps and the Rockies before natural erosion occurred over the last 240 million years leading to what is present today.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian Mountains are a barrier to east–west travel, as they form a series of alternating ridgelines and valleys oriented in opposition to most highways and railroads running east–west.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] This barrier was extremely important in shaping the expansion of the United States in the colonial era.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The range is the home of a very popular recreational feature, the Appalachian Trail.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] This is a 2,175-mile (3,500 km) hiking trail that runs all the way from Mount Katahdin in Maine to Springer Mountain in Georgia, passing over or past a large part of the Appalachian range.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The International Appalachian Trail is an extension of this hiking trail into the Canadian portion of the Appalachian range in New Brunswick and Quebec.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The name was soon altered by the Spanish to Apalachee and used as a name for the tribe and region spreading well inland to the north.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Pánfilo de Narváez's expedition first entered Apalachee territory on June 15, 1528, and applied the name.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Now spelled "Appalachian", it is the fourth-oldest surviving European place-name in the US.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] After the 1540 expedition of Hernando de Soto, Spanish cartographers began to apply the name of the tribe to the mountains themselves.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The first cartographic appearance of *Apalchen* is on Diego Gutiérrez's map of 1562; the first use for the mountain range is the map of Jacques le Moyne de Morgues in 1565.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The name was not commonly used for the whole mountain range until the late 19th century.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] A competing and often more popular name was the "Allegheny Mountains", "Alleghenies", and even "Alleghania".
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In the early 19th century, Washington Irving proposed renaming the United States either Appalachia or Alleghania.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In U.S. dialects in most regions of the Appalachians, the word is pronounced /ˌæpəˈlætʃɪnz/, with the third syllable sounding like "latch".
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In some northern parts of the mountain range, particularly Pennsylvania, it is pronounced /ˌæpəˈleɪtʃɪnz/ or /ˌæpəˈleɪʃɪnz/; the third syllable is like "lay", and the fourth "chins" or "shins".
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] There is often great debate between the residents of the regions regarding the correct pronunciation.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Elsewhere, a commonly accepted pronunciation for the adjective *Appalachian* is /ˌæpəˈlætʃiən/, with the last two syllables "-ian" pronounced as in the word "Romanian".
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] However, each of the governments has an agency that informs the public about the major landforms that make up the countries, the United States Geological Survey (USGS) and the Geological Survey of Canada (GSC).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The landforms are referred to as physiographic regions.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The regions create precise boundaries from which maps can be drawn.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian Highlands is the name of one of the eight physiographic regions of the contiguous 48 United States.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian Uplands is the name of one of seven physiographic regions of Canada.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The second level in the physiographic classification schema for the USGS is "province", the same word as Canada uses to divide its political subdivisions, meaning that the terminology used by the two countries do not match below the region level.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The lowest level of classification is "section".
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian Uplands are one of the seven physiographic divisions in Canada.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Canada's GSC does not use the same classification system as the USGS below the division level.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The agency does break the divisions of the Appalachian Uplands into 13 subsections that are in four different political provinces of Canada.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] While the Appalachian Highlands and Appalachian Uplands are generally continuous across the U.S./Canadian border, the St.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Lawrence Valley area is handled differently in the physiographic classification schemas.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Lawrence Valley in the United States is one of the second-level classifications, part of the Appalachian Highlands.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In Canada, the area is part of the first-level classification, the St.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] This includes the area around the city of Montreal, Anticosti Island, and the northwest coastline of Newfoundland.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The dissected plateau area, while not actually made up of geological mountains, is popularly called "mountains", especially in eastern Kentucky and West Virginia, and while the ridges are not high, the terrain is extremely rugged.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In Ohio and New York, some of the plateau has been glaciated, which has rounded off the sharp ridges and filled the valleys to some extent.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The glaciated regions are usually referred to as hill country rather than mountains.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The mountain system has no axis of dominating altitudes, but in every portion, the summits rise to rather uniform heights, and, especially in the central section, the various ridges and intermontane valleys have the same trend as the system itself.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] None of the summits reaches the region of perpetual snow.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In Pennsylvania, there are over sixty summits that rise over 2,500 ft (800 m); the summits of Mount Davis and Blue Knob rise over 3,000 ft (900 m).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In Maryland, Eagle Rock and Dans Mountain are conspicuous points reaching 3,162 and 2,882 ft (964 and 878 m) respectively.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] On the same side of the Great Valley, south of the Potomac, are the Pinnacle 3,007 feet (917 m) and Pigeon Roost 3,400 ft (1,000 m).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In West Virginia, more than 150 peaks rise above 4,000 ft (1,200 m), including Spruce Knob 4,863 ft (1,482 m), the highest point in the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] A number of other points in the state rise above 4,800 ft (1,500 m).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Cheat Mountain (Snowshoe Mountain) at Thorny Flat 4,848 ft (1,478 m) and Bald Knob 4,842 ft (1,476 m) are among the more notable peaks in West Virginia.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Blue Ridge Mountains, rising in southern Pennsylvania and there known as South Mountain, attain elevations of about 2,000 ft (600 m) in Pennsylvania.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] South Mountain achieves its highest point just below the Mason-Dixon line in Maryland at Quirauk Mountain 2,145 ft (654 m) and then diminishes in height southward to the Potomac River.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Once in Virginia, the Blue Ridge again reaches 2,000 ft (600 m) and higher.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In the Virginia Blue Ridge, the following are some of the highest peaks north of the Roanoke River: Stony Man 4,031 ft (1,229 m), Hawksbill Mountain 4,066 ft (1,239 m), Apple Orchard Mountain 4,225 ft (1,288 m) and Peaks of Otter 4,001 and 3,875 ft (1,220 and 1,181 m).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] South of the Roanoke River, along the Blue Ridge, are Virginia's highest peaks including Whitetop Mountain 5,520 ft (1,680 m) and Mount Rogers 5,729 ft (1,746 m), the highest point in the Commonwealth.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Chief summits in the southern section of the Blue Ridge are located along two main crests, the Western or Unaka Front along the Tennessee-North Carolina border and the Eastern Front in North Carolina, or one of several "cross ridges" between the two main crests.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Prominent summits in the cross ridges include Waterrock Knob (6,292 ft (1,918 m)) in the Plott Balsams.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Across northern Georgia, numerous peaks exceed 4,000 ft (1,200 m), including Brasstown Bald, the state's highest, at 4,784-and-4,696 ft (1,458-and-1,431 m) Rabun Bald.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In north-central Alabama, Mount Cheaha rises prominently to 1,445 feet (440 m) over its surroundings, as part of the southernmost spur of the Blue Ridge Mountains.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Plate tectonics over the period dating back at least 1 billion years led to geological creation of the land that is now the Appalachian Mountain range.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The continental movement led to collisions that built mountains and they later pulled apart creating oceans over parts of the continent that are now exposed.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The first mountain-building tectonic plate collision that initiated the construction of what are today the Appalachians occurred at least a billion years ago when the pre-North American craton called Laurentia collided with at least one other craton — Amazonia.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] All the other cratons of the earth also collided at about this time to form the supercontinent Rodinia and were surrounded by one single ocean.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] (It is possible that the cratons of Kalahari, and Rio Plato, were also part of that early collision since they were present as Rodinia broke up).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Mountain-building referred to as the Grenville Orogeny occurred along the boundaries of the cratons.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The present Appalachian Mountains have at least two areas which are made from rock formations that were formed during this orogeny - the Blue Ridge Mountains and the Adirondacks.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] After the Grenville orogeny, the direction of the continental drift reversed, and the single supercontinent Rodinia began to break up.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The mountains formed during the Grenvillian era underwent erosion due to weathering, glaciation, and other natural processes, resulting in the leveling of the landscape.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The eroded sediments from these mountains contributed to the formation of sedimentary basins and valleys.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] For example, in what is now the southern United States, the Ococee Basin was formed.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Rivers from the surrounding countryside carried clay, silt, sand, and gravel to the basin, much as rivers today carry sediment from the midcontinent region to the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The sediment spread out in layers on the basin floor.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The basin continued to subside, and over a long period of time, probably millions of years, a great thickness of sediment accumulated.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Eventually, the tectonic forces pulling the two continents apart became so strong that an ocean formed off the eastern coast of the Laurentian margin.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] This was called the Iapetus Ocean and was the precursor of the modern Atlantic Ocean.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The rocks of the Valley and Ridge province formed over millions of years, in the Iapetus.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Shells and other hard parts of ancient marine plants and animals accumulated to form limey deposits that later became limestone.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] This is the same process by which limestone forms in modern oceans.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The weathering of limestone, now exposed at the land surface, produces the lime-rich soils that are so prevalent in the fertile farmland of the Valley and Ridge province.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] During this continental break-up, around 600 million to 560 million years ago, volcanic activity was present along the tectonic margins.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] There is evidence of this activity in today's Blue Ridge Mountains.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Mount Rogers, Whitetop Mountain, and Pine Mountain are all the result of volcanic activity that occurred around this time.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Evidence of subsurface activity, dikes and sills intruding into the overlying rock, is present in the Blue Ridge as well.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] For instance, mafic rocks have been found along the Fries Fault in the central Blue Ridge area of Montgomery County, Virginia.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] One of the best examples of mafic rocks from the breakup of Rodina is the Catoctin Formation.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Erupted during the final stages of rifting associated with Rodinia (570-550 Ma), these rocks where later metamorphosed into Greenstone.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Iapetus continued to expand and during that time bacteria, algae, and many species of invertebrates flourished in the oceans, but there were no plants or animals on land.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Then, during the middle Ordovician Period about 500 to 470 million years ago, the motion of the crustal plates changed, and the continents began to move back toward each other.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The once-quiet Appalachian passive margin changed to a very active plate boundary when a neighboring Iapetus oceanic plate containing a volcanic arc collided with and began sinking beneath the North American craton.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Volcanoes grew along the continental margin coincident with the initiation of subduction.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Thrust faulting uplifted and warped older sedimentary rock laid down on the passive margin.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] As the mountains rose, erosion began to wear them down over time.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Streams carried rock debris downslope to be deposited in nearby lowlands.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Taconic orogeny ended after about 60 million years, but built much of the land mass that is now New England and southwestward to Pennsylvania.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Taconic Orogeny was the second of four mountain building plate collisions that contributed to the formation of the Appalachians, culminating in the collision of North America and Africa (see Alleghanian orogeny).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The third mountain-building event was the Acadian orogeny which occurred between 375 and 359 million years ago.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Acadian orogeny was caused by a series of collisions of pieces of crust from the Avalonia Terrane, sections broken off from continent of Gondwana, with the North American Plate.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The collision initiating this orogeny resulted in the closing of the southern Iapetus Ocean and the formation of a high mountain belt.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] After the Acadian collision took place, Gondwana began to retreat from Laurentia with the newly accreted Avalonian terranes left behind.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] As Gondwana moved away, a new ocean opened up, the Rheic Ocean, during the Middle to Late Devonian, and subsequently its closure would result in the formation of the Alleghanian orogeny.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] As the continental plates moved closer together, fragments of oceanic crust, islands, and other continental masses collided with the eastern margin of ancestral North America.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] By this time, plants had appeared on land, followed by scorpions, insects, and amphibians.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The ocean continued to shrink until, about 270 million years ago, the continents that were ancestral to North America and Africa collided during the formation of the supercontinent Pangea.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Because North America and Africa were once geographically connected, the Appalachians formed part of the same mountain chain as the Little Atlas in Morocco.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] This mountain range, known as the Central Pangean Mountains, extended into Scotland, before the Mesozoic Era opening of the Iapetus Ocean, from the North America/Europe collision (See Caledonian orogeny).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] By the end of the Mesozoic Era, the Appalachian Mountains had been eroded to an almost flat plain.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] It was not until the region was uplifted during the Cenozoic Era that the distinctive topography of the present formed.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Uplift rejuvenated the streams, which rapidly responded by cutting downward into the ancient bedrock.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Some streams flowed along weak layers that define the folds and faults created many millions of years earlier.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Other streams downcut so rapidly that they cut right across the resistant folded rocks of the mountain core, carving canyons across rock layers and geologic structures.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian Mountains contain major deposits of anthracite coal as well as bituminous coal.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In the folded mountains the coal is in metamorphosed form as anthracite, represented by the Coal Region of northeastern Pennsylvania.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The bituminous coal fields of western Pennsylvania, western Maryland, southeastern Ohio, eastern Kentucky, southwestern Virginia, and West Virginia contain the sedimentary form of coal.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The mountain top removal method of coal mining, in which entire mountain tops are removed, is currently threatening vast areas and ecosystems of the Appalachian Mountain region.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The surface coal mining that started in the 1940s has significantly impacted the central Appalachian Mountains in Kentucky, Tennessee, Virginia and West Virginia.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Early mining methods were unregulated and mined land reclamation research, including acid base accounting, was led by the West Virginia University in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] West Virginia developed rigorous mine reclamation standards for state coal mines in the late 1960s.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Regulations were introduced by most states to protect the Appalachian Mountains by the late 1960s.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Social and political activism brought about the Surface Mining Control and Reclamation Act of 1977.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The 1859 discovery of commercial quantities of petroleum in the Appalachian Mountains of western Pennsylvania started the modern United States petroleum industry.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Recent discoveries of commercial natural gas deposits in the Marcellus Shale formation and Utica Shale formations have once again focused oil industry attention on the Appalachian Basin.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Some plateaus of the Appalachian Mountains contain metallic minerals such as iron and zinc.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] There are many geological issues concerning the rivers and streams of the Appalachians.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In spite of the existence of the Great Appalachian Valley, many of the main rivers are transverse to the mountain system axis.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The drainage divide of the Appalachians follows a tortuous course that crosses the mountainous belt just north of the New River in Virginia.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In the northern section, the height of land lies on the inland side of the mountainous belt, and thus the main lines of drainage run from north to south, exemplified by the Hudson River.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] However, the valley through which the Hudson River flows was cut by the gigantic glaciers of the ice ages—the same glaciers that deposited their terminal moraines in southern New York and formed the east–west Long Island.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian region is generally considered the geographical divide between the eastern seaboard of the United States and the Midwest region of the country.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Eastern Continental Divide follows the Appalachian Mountains from Pennsylvania to Georgia.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachians, particularly the Central and Southern regions, is one of the most biodiverse places in North America.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The north–south orientation of the long ridges and valleys contributes to the high number of plant and animal species.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Species were able to migrate through these from either direction during alternating periods of warming and cooling, settling in the microclimates that best suited them.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The flora of the Appalachians are diverse and vary primarily in response to geology, latitude, elevation and moisture availability.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Geobotanically, they constitute a floristic province of the North American Atlantic Region.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachians consist primarily of deciduous broad-leaf trees and evergreen needle-leaf conifers, but also contain the evergreen broad-leaf American holly (*Ilex opaca*), and the deciduous needle-leaf conifer, the tamarack, or eastern larch (*Larix laricina*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The dominant northern and high elevation conifer is the red spruce (*Picea rubens*), which grows from near sea level to above 4,000 ft (1,200 m) above sea level (asl) in northern New England and southeastern Canada.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] It also grows southward along the Appalachian crest to the highest elevations of the southern Appalachians, as in North Carolina and Tennessee.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In the central Appalachians it is usually confined above 3,000 ft (900 m) asl, except for a few cold valleys in which it reaches lower elevations.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In the southern Appalachians, it is restricted to higher elevations.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Another species is the black spruce (*Picea mariana*), which extends farthest north of any conifer in North America, is found at high elevations in the northern Appalachians, and in bogs as far south as Pennsylvania.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachians are also home to two species of fir, the boreal balsam fir (*Abies balsamea*), and the southern high elevation endemic, Fraser fir (*Abies fraseri*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Fraser fir is endemic to the highest parts of the southern Appalachian Mountains, where along with red spruce it forms a fragile ecosystem known as the Southern Appalachian spruce–fir forest.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Fraser fir rarely occurs below 5,500 ft (1,700 m), and becomes the dominant tree type at 6,200 ft (1,900 m).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] By contrast, balsam fir is found from near sea level to the tree line in the northern Appalachians, but ranges only as far south as Virginia and West Virginia in the central Appalachians, where it is usually confined above 3,900 ft (1,200 m) asl, except in cold valleys.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Curiously, it is associated with oaks in Virginia.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The balsam fir of Virginia and West Virginia is thought by some to be a natural hybrid between the more northern variety and Fraser fir.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] While red spruce is common in both upland and bog habitats, balsam fir, as well as black spruce and tamarack, are more characteristic of the latter.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] However, balsam fir also does well in soils with a pH as high as 6.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Eastern or Canada hemlock (*Tsuga canadensis*) is another important evergreen needle-leaf conifer that grows along the Appalachian chain from north to south but is confined to lower elevations than red spruce and the firs.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] It generally occupies richer and less acidic soils than the spruce and firs and is characteristic of deep, shaded and moist mountain valleys and coves.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] It is subject to the hemlock woolly adelgid (*Adelges tsugae*), an introduced insect, that is rapidly extirpating it as a forest tree.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Less abundant, and restricted to the southern Appalachians, is Carolina hemlock (*Tsuga caroliniana*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Like Canada hemlock, this tree suffers severely from the hemlock woolly adelgid.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Several species of pines characteristic of the Appalachians are eastern white pine (*Pinus strobus*), Virginia pine (*Pinus virginiana*), pitch pine (*Pinus rigida*), Table Mountain pine (*Pinus pungens*) and shortleaf pine (*Pinus echinata*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Red pine (*Pinus resinosa*) is a boreal species that forms a few high elevation outliers as far south as West Virginia.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] All of these species except white pine tend to occupy sandy, rocky, poor soil sites, which are mostly acidic in character.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] White pine, a large species valued for its timber, tends to do best in rich, moist soil, either acidic or alkaline in character.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Pitch pine is also at home in acidic, boggy soil, and Table Mountain pine may occasionally be found in this habitat as well.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Shortleaf pine is generally found in warmer habitats and at lower elevations than the other species.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] All the species listed do best in open or lightly shaded habitats, although white pine also thrives in shady coves, valleys, and on floodplains.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachians are characterized by a wealth of large, beautiful deciduous broadleaf (hardwood) trees.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Their occurrences are best summarized and described in E.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Lucy Braun's 1950 classic, *Deciduous Forests of Eastern North America* (Macmillan, New York).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The most diverse and richest forests are the mixed-mesophytic or medium-moisture types, which are largely confined to rich, moist montane soils of the southern and central Appalachians, particularly in the Cumberland and Allegheny Mountains, but also thrive in the southern Appalachian coves.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Characteristic canopy species are white basswood (*Tilia heterophylla*), yellow buckeye (*Aesculus octandra*), sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*), American beech (*Fagus grandifolia*), tuliptree (*Liriodendron tulipifera*), white ash (*Fraxinus americana*) and yellow birch (*Betula alleganiensis*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Other common trees are red maple (*Acer rubrum*), shagbark and bitternut hickories (*Carya ovata* and *C. cordiformis*) and black or sweet birch (*Betula lenta*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Small understory trees and shrubs include paw paw (*Asimina tribola*), flowering dogwood (*Cornus florida*), hophornbeam (*Ostrya virginiana*), witch-hazel (*Hamamelis virginiana*) and spicebush (*Lindera benzoin*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] There are also hundreds of perennial and annual herbs, among them such herbal and medicinal plants as American ginseng (*Panax quinquefolius*), goldenseal (*Hydrastis canadensis*), bloodroot (*Sanguinaria canadensis*) and black cohosh (*Cimicifuga racemosa*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The foregoing trees, shrubs, and herbs are also more widely distributed in less rich mesic forests that generally occupy coves, stream valleys and flood plains throughout the southern and central Appalachians at low and intermediate elevations.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Drier and rockier uplands and ridges are occupied by oak–chestnut forests dominated by a variety of oaks (*Quercus* spp.), hickories (*Carya* spp.) and, in the past, by the American chestnut (*Castanea dentata*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The American chestnut was virtually eliminated as a canopy species by the introduced fungal chestnut blight (*Cryphonectaria parasitica*), but lives on as sapling-sized sprouts that originate from roots, which are not killed by the fungus.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In present-day forest canopies, chestnut has been largely replaced by oaks.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The oak forests of the southern and central Appalachians consist largely of black, northern red, white, chestnut and scarlet oaks (*Quercus velutina*, *Q. rubra*, *Q. alba*, *Q. prinus* and *Q. coccinea*) and hickories, such as the pignut (*Carya glabra*) in particular.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The richest forests, which grade into mesic types, usually in coves and on gentle slopes, have predominantly white and northern red oaks, while the driest sites are dominated by chestnut oak, or sometimes by scarlet or northern red oaks.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In the northern Appalachians the oaks, except for white and northern red, drop out, while the latter extends farthest north.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The oak forests generally lack the diverse small tree, shrub and herb layers of mesic forests.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The evergreen great rhododendron (*Rhododendron maximum*) is characteristic of moist stream valleys.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] These occurrences are in line with the prevailing acidic character of most oak forest soils.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In contrast, the much rarer chinquapin oak (*Quercus muehlenbergii*) demands alkaline soils and generally grows where limestone rock is near the surface.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Hence no ericaceous shrubs are associated with it.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian flora also include a diverse assemblage of bryophytes (mosses and liverworts), as well as fungi.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] As with vascular plants, these tend to be closely related to the character of the soils and the thermal environment in which they are found.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Eastern deciduous forests are subject to a number of serious insect and disease outbreaks.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Among the most conspicuous is that of the introduced spongy moth (*Lymantria dispar*), which infests primarily oaks, causing severe defoliation and tree mortality.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] But it also has the benefit of eliminating weak individuals, and thus improving the genetic stock, as well as creating rich habitat of a type through accumulation of dead wood.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Because hardwoods sprout so readily, this moth is not as harmful as the hemlock woolly adelgid.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Perhaps more serious is the introduced beech bark disease complex, which includes both a scale insect (*Cryptococcus fagisuga*) and fungal components.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] During the 19th and early 20th centuries, the Appalachian forests were subject to severe and destructive logging and land clearing, which resulted in the designation of the national forests and parks as well many state-protected areas.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] However, these and a variety of other destructive activities continue, albeit in diminished forms; and thus far only a few ecologically based management practices have taken hold.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Appalachian bogs are boreal ecosystems, which occur in many places in the Appalachians, particularly the Allegheny and Blue Ridge subranges.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Though popularly called bogs, many of them are technically fens.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Several mountain summits in the southern Appalachians are covered with expansive open habitats (either grassy meadows or heath) known as Appalachian balds.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] These habitats support many unique plant and animal communities, including rare, relict species, that are adapted to the open, exposed habitat.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Others, especially those dominated by introduced grasses, may be fully anthropogenic in origin.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The abandonment of grazing has caused trees to encroach on many of these balds, threatening their ecosystems.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Animals that characterize the Appalachian forests include five species of tree squirrels.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The most commonly seen is the low to moderate elevation eastern gray squirrel (*Sciurus carolinensis*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Occupying similar habitat is the slightly larger fox squirrel (*Sciurus niger*) and the much smaller southern flying squirrel (*Glaucomys volans*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] As familiar as squirrels are the eastern cottontail rabbit (*Silvilagus floridanus*) and the white-tailed deer (*Odocoileus virginianus*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The latter in particular has greatly increased in abundance as a result of the extirpation of the eastern wolf (*Canis lupus lycaon*) and the North American cougar.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] This has led to the overgrazing and browsing of many plants of the Appalachian forests, as well as destruction of agricultural crops.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Other deer include the moose (*Alces alces*), found only in the north, and the elk (*Cervus canadensis*), which, although once extirpated, is now making a comeback, through transplantation, in the southern and central Appalachians.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] In Quebec, the Chic-Chocs host the only population of reindeer (*Rangifer tarandus*) south of the St.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] An additional species that is common in the north but extends its range southward at high elevations to Virginia and West Virginia is the varying or snowshoe hare (*Lepus americanus*).
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] However, these central Appalachian populations are scattered and very small.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Another species of great interest is the beaver (*Castor canadensis*), which is showing a great resurgence in numbers after its near extirpation for its pelt.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] This resurgence is bringing about a drastic alteration in habitat through the construction of dams and other structures throughout the mountains.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] European boars (*Sus scrofa*) were introduced in the early 20th century.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Of great importance are the many species of salamanders and, in particular, the lungless species (family Plethodontidae) that live in great abundance concealed by leaves and debris, on the forest floor.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Most frequently seen, however, is the eastern or red-spotted newt (*Notophthalmus viridescens*), whose terrestrial eft form is often encountered on the open, dry forest floor.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] It has been estimated that salamanders represent the largest class of animal biomass in the Appalachian forests.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Frogs and toads are of lesser diversity and abundance, but the wood frog (*Rana sylvatica*) is, like the eft, commonly encountered on the dry forest floor, while a number of species of small frogs, such as spring peepers (*Pseudacris crucifer*), enliven the forest with their calls.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Salamanders and other amphibians contribute greatly to nutrient cycling through their consumption of small life forms on the forest floor and in aquatic habitats.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Although reptiles are less abundant and diverse than amphibians, a number of snakes are conspicuous members of the fauna.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] One of the largest is the non-venomous black rat snake (*Elaphe obsoleta obsoleta*), while the common garter snake (*Thamnophis sirtalis*) is among the smallest but most abundant.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The eastern copperhead (*Agkistrodon contortrix*) and the timber rattler (*Crotalus horridus*) are venomous pit vipers.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] There are few lizards, but the broad-headed skink (*Eumeces laticeps*), at up to 13 in (33 cm) in length, and an excellent climber and swimmer, is one of the largest and most spectacular in appearance and action.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] The most common turtle is the eastern box turtle (*Terrapene carolina carolina*), which is found in both upland and lowland forests in the central and southern Appalachians.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Prominent among aquatic species is the large common snapping turtle (*Chelydra serpentina*), which occurs throughout the Appalachians.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Appalachian streams are notable for their highly diverse freshwater fish life.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Among the most abundant and diverse are those of the minnow family (family Cyprinidae), while species of the colorful darters (*Percina* spp.) are also abundant.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] A characteristic fish of shaded, cool Appalachian forest streams is the wild brook or speckled trout (*Salvelinus fontinalis*), which is much sought after as a game fish.
[src:barbulanympha/appalachian-mountains] Water Striders (family *Gerridae*) are insects commonly seen on the surface of calm streams and ponds.
[src:barbulanympha/axostyle] An **axostyle** is a sheet of microtubules found in certain protists.
[src:barbulanympha/axostyle] It arises from the bases of the flagella, sometimes projecting beyond the end of the cell, and is often flexible or contractile, and so may be involved in movement and provides support for the cell.
[src:barbulanympha/axostyle] Axostyles originate in association with a flagellar microtubular root and occur in two groups, the oxymonads and parabasalids; they have different structures and are not homologous.
[src:barbulanympha/axostyle] Within trichomonads the axostyle has been theorised to participate in locomotion and cell adhesion, but also karyokinesis during cell division.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] A large nucleus is contained in a membranous nuclear sleeve in the anterior portion of the cell.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] The interphase chromatin granules are larger than those of other genera.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] The nucleus is connected with the nuclear membrane by many fibers or strands, which become the intranuclear chromosomal fibers when chromosomes develop.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] Both chromatin and plastid nucleoli are present.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] *Barbulanympha* possesses two centrioles.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] In the larger species, each centriole is about 30 microns long, while in the smaller species it is a little more than half this length.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] Their proximal ends are slightly enlarged and connected by a desmose.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] The distal ends of the centrioles are surrounded by centrosomes.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] The number of axostyles in *Barbulanympha* varies from an average of 80 in the smallest species to an average of 350 in the largest species.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] Each axostyle is composed of several fibers.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] There are approximately the same number of parabasals in each species of *Barbulanympha* as axostyles.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] The thread of the parabasal then increases in size to form the body, which is sausage shaped.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] Underneath each flagellated area is a half-cone shaped structure, the parabasal-axostylar lamella.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] The parabasals and axostyles are attached to this structure.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] During cell division, *Barbulanympha* has a distinct two-stage anaphase.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] In anaphase-A, the chromosomal spindle fibres shorten, pulling the chromosomes towards the stationary centrosomes located at the poles of the central spindle.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] Importantly, the central spindle does not elongate during this phase.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] The nuclear envelope forms a seam anterior to the spindle and transforms the nucleus into a sleeve surrounding the central spindle.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] Following anaphase-A, anaphase-B commences with the elongation of the central spindle, which can increase up to fivefold.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] This elongation pushes the "telophasic" bouquets of chromosomes, still connected to the centrosomes by the shortened chromosomal fibres, further apart.
[src:barbulanympha/barbulanympha] During this stage, a cleft opens in the nuclear seam and expands, progressively exposing the central spindle and eventually partitioning the nucleus into two daughter nuclei.
